In saturation mode $\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{CE}}=0$<br><br><img src="https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1lgznn3k9/3a47cd32-db85-4075-bc55-921f6dab50e8/f7152b90-e544-11ed-8d50-d941312069b0/file-1lgznn3ka.png?format=png" data-orsrc="https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1lgznn3k9/3a47cd32-db85-4075-bc55-921f6dab50e8/f7152b90-e544-11ed-8d50-d941312069b0/file-1lgznn3ka.png" loading="lazy" style="max-width: 100%;height: auto;display: block;margin: 0 auto;max-height: 50vh" alt="JEE Main 2023 (Online) 8th April Evening Shift Physics - Semiconductor Question 66 English Explanation"><br>
Now<br><br>
$$
\begin{aligned}
&amp; \mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{CC}}-\mathrm{I}_{\mathrm{c}} \mathrm{R}_{\mathrm{c}}=0 ~~~~\text{(from KVL)}\\\\
&amp; \Rightarrow \mathrm{I}_{\mathrm{b}}=\frac{\mathrm{V}_{\mathrm{CC}}}{\mathrm{R}_{\mathrm{C}}}=\frac{1}{1 \times 10^3}=10^{-3} \mathrm{~A}
\end{aligned}
$$<br><br>
Given that<br><br>
$$
\beta=100=\frac{I_c}{I_b}
$$<br><br>
$\begin{aligned} &amp; \Rightarrow \mathrm{I}_b=\frac{\mathrm{I}_c}{100}=\frac{10^{-3}}{100}=10^{-5} \mathrm{~A} \\\\ &amp; \Rightarrow \mathrm{I}_b=10 \mu \mathrm{A}\end{aligned}$

